        return False
    for I in range(2, int(n**0.5) + 1):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False
    return True
```

This function takes a single argument `n`, which represents the number you want to check for primality. The function first checks if the input number is less than or equal to one (which is not considered prime), and returns False in this case. Otherwise, it iterates over all possible factors of the input number from two through its square root, inclusive. If any factor is found, the function immediately returns False indicating that the number is composite rather than prime. Finally, if no factor is found within the loop, the function returns True indicating that the input number is prime. This function follows best practices such as using descriptive variable names and clear comments. It also has good performance characteristics due to stopping at the square root instead of checking every integer between 2 and itself.

To generate an automatic table of contents (TOC) in a LaTeX document, you need to include the following command:

```
\tableofcontents
```

This command should come after all the chapter and section headings have been defined. The TOC will then appear at the beginning of the document, listing out all the chapters and sections with their corresponding page numbers.

Here's an example of a simple LaTeX file that includes a TOC using this method:

```
\documentclass{article}
\title{My Document Title}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
    \maketitle

    \section{Section One}
    This is some text for Section One.

    \subsection{Sub-section One}
    Here's some content for Sub-section One.

    \section{Section Two}
    This is another section for my document.

    \subsection{Sub-section Two}
    And here's more text for Sub-section Two.

    \tableofcontents

    \clearpage

    \section{Section Three}
    Yet another section!

    \subsection{Sub-section Three}
    Check out this cool stuff in Sub-section Three.

    \end{document}
```

In this example, we first define our title, author, and date information using the `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands respectively. Then, we create several sections and subsections with appropriate titles using the `\section` and `\subsection` commands. Afterwards, we add the `\tableofcontents` command before moving on to additional sections and content as usual. Finally, we use `\clearpage` to ensure there is no overlap between the TOC and subsequent content when generating the PDF output.

