Yes, we can solve this problem using bit manipulation techniques instead of loops or recursion. The idea is to repeatedly divide the input number by three and check for division with remainder zero until either n becomes one (indicating a power of three) or n reaches zero. Here's the code:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    int logValue;
    while ((logValue = Integer.numberOfTrailingZeros(n)) > 0) {
        n >>>= logValue; // shift right by log value bits
    }
    return n == 1;
}
```

This function uses `Integer.numberOfTrailingZeros()` method which returns the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of the given number. If the result is greater than 0, then we divide n by 3^logValue and continue checking until n is reduced to 1. This process ensures that any non-power of three will eventually reach zero after dividing, so returning false at that point.

Note: This implementation has time complexity O(log N), making it efficient compared to iterative solutions.

